<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Carlos V. Lozano 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 HELP WANTED: Since the Ventura County chapter of the Red Cross began its 
fund-raising drive to aid Rwandan refugees six weeks ago, only one check has 
arrived . . . for $40. "Normally, the typical response to international 
emergencies is a few thousand dollars," said chapter Director Brian E. Bolton. 
In part, he thinks, people feel overwhelmed by the enormity of the African 
crisis. "I compare it to all the people in Ventura County leaving and walking 
into Santa Barbara, and having no way to feed them," Bolton said. Donations can 
be sent to Rwanda Relief c/o American Red Cross, P.O. Box 5850, Ventura, Calif. 
93005-5850. 
</P>
<P>
 HOME IMPROVEMENT: Speaking of humanitarian efforts . . . about 30 Simi Valley 
residents recently returned from Bud, W. Va., where they helped repair the 
homes of needy families as part of the Appalachian Service Project. The group 
of volunteers, ranging in age from 13 to 74, raised $29,000 to pay their own 
expenses. They did everything from roof to plumbing repairs. Said one 
volunteer: "The goal of the project was to make homes warmer, safer and drier." 
</P>
<P>
 OFF THE AIR: KDSK is Ventura County's only public access radio station. And 
its days are numbered (B6) . . . . Ventura County Cablevision, which transmits 
the station's programming, has decided to pull the plug on KDSK. . . . During 
its 10-year run, the nonprofit station has given many would-be disc jockeys a 
chance to ride the airwaves for free. Said disc-jockey Derek Underhill: "It's a 
small-town radio station with a small-town feeling. It would be a shame to let 
it die." 
</P>
<P>
 PAYING TRIBUTE: In memory of her late son, Richard, Carolyn Adams purchased 
for $100 an inscription on a plaque at the Ventura Pier (B1) . . . . Money 
collected from inscriptions continues to trickle in for a fund to keep the pier 
in good repair. "When you have someone and you love them and you lose them," 
said Adams, "the worst fear you have is that people will forget about him." 
</P>
</TEXT>
