ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: GARDEN GROVE; LUNCHEON WILL FOCUS ON SITUATION IN KOREA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A discussion of the current events on the Korean Peninsula will be the 
highlight of this year's "friendship luncheon" hosted by the Garden Grove 
Sister City Assn. on Thursday at the Dragon Palace Restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
 Joyce Yoo, who recently graduated from Cal State Long Beach with a history 
major, will discuss "Understanding Korea -- South and North," focusing on how 
the death of North Korean leader Kim Il Sung could affect the relations of the 
two countries and the rest of the world. 
</P>
<P>
 Yoo will also talk about Korean culture and why Korean-American families put 
high emphasis on education. The talk and lunch take place from 11:30 a.m. to 2 
p.m. Tickets are $12 each. 
</P>
<P>
 The Korean American Assn. of Orange County, one of the largest Korean-American 
groups in California with more than 10,000 members, is co-hosting the event. 
</P>
<P>
 Ray Yong Choi, a master of the Autoharp, will provide the entertainment. 
</P>
