<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: MOORPARK; CHANGES SOUGHT AT DEADLY RAIL CROSSING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A recent fatal head-on collision at a railroad crossing west of Moorpark has 
prompted city officials to step up efforts to pressure the state Department of 
Transportation or the Southern Pacific railroad to make the crossing safer. 
</P>
<P>
 The July 9 accident was the second fatal head-on collision at the crossing in 
less than a week, officials said.The crossing -- at California 118, just west 
of Grimes Canyon Road -- was listed by the state Public Utilities Commission as 
the 37th most-dangerous crossing in the state. 
</P>
<P>
 City officials contend that while there have been no accidents involving 
trains at the crossing in recent memory, the crossing's configuration makes it 
easy for drivers to drift into oncoming traffic. 
</P>
<P>
 The track runs parallel to the two-lane highway on both sides of the crossing, 
which resembles a distended X . Crossing gates and flashing lights stop traffic 
on the highway, which has a posted speed limit of 55 m.p.h. 
</P>
<P>
 Southern Pacific officials say that because other crossings in the state have 
proven more dangerous, they do not have immediate plans to significantly alter 
the design of the crossing. 
</P>
<P>
 Supervisor Vicky Howard, who said she drives over the crossing at least twice 
a day, told the Moorpark City Council she has been pushing to make the road and 
rail-line intersection safer. 
</P>
<P>
 "The problem is that it's a Southern Pacific crossing and they're not 
cooperating," Howard said. 
</P>
<P>
 Under county pressure, Caltrans has made some improvements to the asphalt 
around the track. Howard said Southern Pacific has been more receptive to 
laying concrete around the tracks where the asphalt has turned bumpy. SCOTT 
HADLY 
</P>
</TEXT>
