<HEADLINE>
<P>
IMAGINATION TAKES FLIGHT AT CLOSE OF VALLEY FAIR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAKI BECKER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Shut up and jump! 
</P>
<P>
 So dared the T-shirts worn by the self-professed adrenaline-addicted employees 
of Bungee Outerlimits, one of the most popular new attractions at the San 
Fernando Valley Fair. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm hooked!" declared rookie jumper Melissa Kephart of Burbank, clambering 
off the enormous yellow safety cushion after making a mighty backward leap from 
the top of the bungee tower. "It's taken me two days to work up the nerve to do 
this," said the twentysomething Kephart, who squeezed in her perilous plunge on 
the last day of the fair. 
</P>
<P>
 An estimated four-day total of 51,000 people braved the scorching heat at the 
Los Angeles Equestrian Center in Burbank for the 48th San Fernando Valley Fair, 
sponsored by the 51st District Agricultural Assn. For those who prefer less 
pulse-pounding pleasures than bungee diving, there were carnival rides, cold 
lemonade and soap- and lace-making demonstrations. 
</P>
<P>
 But not everybody loved the event. On Saturday, the activist group Last Chance 
for Animals displayed banners and handed out leaflets at the fair's entrance to 
protest the treatment of bulls in the two Bull-O-Rama events. Fair spokeswoman 
Georgia Cluver said the protesters dispersed after being told by police that 
they would be arrested for demonstrating on private property. 
</P>
<P>
 On Sunday, the fair's management closed some rides to prevent patrons from 
getting blisters caused by the sun pounding down on metallic seats and slides. 
</P>
<P>
 But there was no lack of activities to keep Valley residents entertained. 
</P>
<P>
 To take on the flesh-sucking effects of centrifugal force, sisters Nicole, 14, 
and Jennifer Keith, 10, of Chatsworth hopped on a giant, revolving wheel called 
Roundup. Jennifer said Roundup is one of her favorite rides because she likes 
to get dizzy. 
</P>
<P>
 Marisa and Adam Van Houten, ages 7 and 4, opted to play Simon Says at Kids 
Games, under the shade of the Children's Fun Stage. 
</P>
<P>
 Some guests walked away from the fair with a balloon and cotton candy in hand, 
having tasted a piece of old-fashioned America. Then there were people who will 
remember the 48th San Fernando Valley Fair for their daredevil jumps. Said 
Kephart: "It was the most exciting thing I've ever done in my life." 
</P>
</TEXT>
