<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCHULTZ BRINGS HIS ATTITUDE TO THE RAMS; FOOTBALL: OFFENSIVE LINEMAN NOT 
INTERESTED IN MAKING A GOOD IMPRESSION ANYWHERE BUT ON THE FOOTBALL FIELD. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By T.J. SIMERS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Meet Bill Schultz, the goofy-looking offensive lineman with the Mohawk 
haircut, goatee and surly disposition. 
</P>
<P>
 OK, so the Indianapolis Colts weren't impressed -- they cut him. 
</P>
<P>
 "They said it was due to me making so much money," Schultz said. "But I think 
the coaching staff just didn't like me very much." 
</P>
<P>
 Understandable. 
</P>
<P>
 "I've had a couple of the guys tell me to cut the tail off," Schultz said, 
"and I've just looked at them and told them to kiss (off)." 
</P>
<P>
 Four years in Indianapolis before the Colts cut him? 
</P>
<P>
 "To have a place on the team I shouldn't have to kiss (up to anyone)." 
</P>
<P>
 First impressions sometimes can be deceiving. 
</P>
<P>
 "People are going to see a mean (individual) on the field," Schultz said. "If 
I'm going to run block somebody I'm going to put them on their (behind). 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm not here to impress anyone. I'm here to do a job. I'll wear the same set 
of clothing all month, I don't care. I'm not here to smell good. I've got one 
job and that's to play well on the football field. If I stink, fine." 
</P>
<P>
 Future interviews, of course, will be conducted via telephone, but while the 
winds are blowing right there's still time to learn more about Mr. 
Congeniality. 
</P>
<P>
 William Schultz, raised in Granada Hills, was the starting left tackle for USC 
in the 1990 Rose Bowl victory over Michigan. He was forced into action against 
Lawrence Taylor in his rookie season for the Colts. "Held the hell out of him 
and he called me every name in the book," Schultz said. 
</P>
<P>
 He owns a Corvette and Harley Davidson -- each with the license plate: Mohawk. 
He has a ton of superstitions. He blamed his release in Indianapolis on the 
fact that he shaved his head bald. He credits his good fortune in joining the 
Rams on the fact that he switched to a Mohawk cut the day before the team hired 
him. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm very superstitious," he said. "I put my left sock on first before every 
game, write my grandmother's name on my wrist tape before putting on my gloves, 
walk on the field to see how my shoes feel before putting on my pads and then 
throw up once or twice." 
</P>
<P>
 He gets steamed when people tell him he looks goofy, and downright hot asked 
if he owns a mirror and ever uses it. 
</P>
<P>
 "I thought about cutting my hair off and coming in like everybody else, but 
I'm not like everybody else. I'm one of a kind," Schultz said. 
</P>
<P>
 "I could not go out tomorrow and get a job paying me the money I make. A lot 
of people in this game don't seem to understand that." 
</P>
<P>
 The Rams understand and like him. 
</P>
<P>
 "If you got four earrings I don't give a damn," said offensive line coach Jim 
Erkenbeck. "I kind of like the Mohawk. Individuality. 
</P>
<P>
 "This guy can play. He volunteered to play left tackle for us. He wants to 
make this team, will make this team, and is glad to be back in Southern 
California." 
</P>
<P>
 The Rams like him so much that they have a plan to move him to left guard and 
challenge Tom Newberry. 
</P>
<P>
 And Schultz is ready to do whatever it takes to make the team. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're all friends now; on the field we're not friends," he said. "I got cut, 
and for the first month I didn't leave my house. You're nothing suddenly; 
you're not anything special. I was scared. I thought it was all over for me." 
</P>
<P>
 Stinky, but motivated, Schultz is back on the job and a good training camp 
away from winning full-time employment. 
</P>
<P>
 "You lose a job and it makes you see the light," Schultz said. "I'm going to 
bust my (butt)." 
</P>
</TEXT>
