<P>
SOUTHLAND PREVIEW / THE BUSINESS WEEK AHEAD: SOUTHLAND; HOME SALES STATISTICS 
DUE: 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The California Assn. of Realtors is scheduled to release figures today for 
June sales, and the report should provide one of the first solid indicators of 
how rising mortgage rates have affected Southern California's key housing 
industry.Rates on 30-year loans have jumped to about 8.5% from 7% in February, 
adding nearly $150 to the monthly cost of a $150,000 fixed-rate loan. Sales in 
Southern California rose in the spring as "fence sitters" finally decided to 
buy before rates went higher. But the rush slowed as rates kept climbing. The 
June figures should show whether buyers are staying on the sidelines or have 
shaken off their rate hike fears and jumped back into the market. 
</P>
